    <!-- SECTION 1 -->
    <h2>The Short Answer — With the Math</h2>

    <p>A 200lb man weighs approximately 91 kilograms. The research-backed protein target for men over 40 is 1.2–1.6g per kilogram of bodyweight per day. That puts the range at:</p>

    <div class="compare-grid">
      <div class="compare-card bad">
        <div class="cc-label">❌ What 100g actually is</div>
        <div class="cc-num">1.1g/kg</div>
        <div class="cc-desc">Just below the minimum research-backed threshold of 1.2g/kg. Better than average — but not enough.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-card good">
        <div class="cc-label">✓ Where you should be</div>
        <div class="cc-num">109–145g</div>
        <div class="cc-desc">1.2g/kg (floor) to 1.6g/kg (optimal for active men). This is where muscle preservation research consistently points.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>100g isn't a disaster. It's dramatically better than the 50–70g most men are actually eating. But for a 200lb man trying to preserve or build muscle after 40, it still leaves a 9–45g daily gap depending on your activity level. That gap compounds quietly over months and years.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 2 -->
    <h2>Why the RDA Gets This So Wrong</h2>

    <p>The standard RDA for protein is 0.8g per kilogram of bodyweight. For a 200lb man, that's approximately 73g per day. If you're eating 100g, you're already 37% above the RDA — which probably feels like you're doing well.</p>

    <p>The problem is what the RDA was actually designed to do: prevent protein deficiency in healthy young adults. It was never intended as a muscle-preservation target for men in their 40s, 50s, and 60s. The research literature on older adults consistently lands 50–100% higher than the RDA.</p>

    <div class="science-strip">
      <h3>What the Research Actually Shows</h3>
      <div class="science-item">
        <div class="science-num">1.2g</div>
        <div class="science-text"><strong>per kg/day — the conservative floor.</strong> A 2019 meta-analysis of protein requirements in older adults published in the American Journal of Clinical Nutrition found that the average requirement for older men was significantly above the RDA, with 1.2g/kg as a practical minimum for muscle maintenance.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="science-item">
        <div class="science-num">1.6g</div>
        <div class="science-text"><strong>per kg/day — the evidence-based upper range.</strong> A landmark 2018 systematic review and meta-analysis in the British Journal of Sports Medicine found that protein intakes beyond 1.62g/kg/day showed diminishing returns for muscle gain — meaning this is effectively the ceiling of meaningful benefit.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="science-item">
        <div class="science-num">30g+</div>
        <div class="science-text"><strong>per meal — the per-sitting threshold.</strong> Research from Dr. Stuart Phillips at McMaster University and others has consistently shown that older adults require at least 30g of protein per meal — with some studies suggesting 40g — to maximally stimulate muscle protein synthesis due to <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/" style="color:var(--green-light);">anabolic resistance</a>.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 3 - THE MEAL MATH -->
    <h2>The Per-Meal Problem Nobody Talks About</h2>

    <p>Here's where 100g falls apart even if the daily total was acceptable — the math inside each meal.</p>

    <p>Muscle protein synthesis isn't triggered by your daily total. It's triggered by each individual meal crossing a leucine threshold — the amino acid that acts as the "on switch" for muscle building. After 40, that threshold rises. Research consistently points to 30g per meal as the minimum dose for meaningful muscle protein synthesis in older adults.</p>

    <p>Watch what happens when you divide 100g across a normal eating day:</p>

    <div class="meal-math">
      <div class="meal-math-header">
        <h4>100g/day ÷ 4 meals — the per-meal reality</h4>
        <div class="mm-sub">200lb man, over 40</div>
      </div>
      <div class="mm-row">
        <div class="mm-meal"><strong>Breakfast</strong>2 eggs + toast + coffee</div>
        <div>
          <div class="mm-g short">~18g</div>
