    <p>The highlighted row — 109g — is where a 200lb man over 40 crosses from "below the floor" into "at minimum." Every gram below 109g is deficit territory for muscle preservation. 100g keeps you 9g short of even the conservative floor.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 5 -->
    <h2>What Happens When You Stay at 100g Long-Term</h2>

    <p>Nothing dramatic. That's the insidious part.</p>

    <p>You don't suddenly feel weaker or notice muscle loss month to month. What happens is slow and cumulative: you lose 0.5–1% of muscle mass per year in the 40s, accelerating to 1–2% per year after 60. That rate is meaningfully influenced by whether you're hitting your protein floor. At 100g, a 200lb man is likely in slow-loss territory rather than maintenance territory.</p>

    <p>Over five years, the compounding difference between 100g and 130g daily isn't theoretical. It shows up as reduced strength, slower recovery, harder body composition changes, and a metabolism that responds less efficiently to training. These things don't announce themselves. They just accumulate.</p>

    <p>This is why sarcopenia — age-related muscle loss — is called a silent epidemic. It happens in the gap between what feels like enough and what actually is enough. For more on the mechanism, <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/sarcopenia-men-over-40/">the sarcopenia post</a> covers it in detail.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 6 -->
    <h2>How to Close the Gap Without Overhauling Everything</h2>

    <p>The jump from 100g to 120–130g is genuinely achievable without adding a new meal or dramatically changing what you eat. For most men it comes down to three adjustments:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Fix breakfast first.</strong> Most men's biggest protein deficit is in the morning. A breakfast that hits 40–50g sets the day up completely differently. The <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/50g-protein-breakfast-men-over-40/">50g protein breakfast post</a> has six specific combos that get there without a shake.</li>
      <li><strong>Upgrade one meal anchor.</strong> Swap a protein-light lunch for one built around a larger protein source — 6oz of chicken, a can of tuna, cottage cheese as a base. That single change adds 15–20g per day.</li>
      <li><strong>Track it for one week.</strong> You cannot close a gap you can't see. Most men are surprised to find out exactly which meals are dragging their daily number down. A week of tracking shows the pattern clearly — and usually, the fix is obvious once you see it.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>You don't need to redesign your diet. You need visibility into what's already happening and two or three targeted adjustments. That's it.</p>

