      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is 100g of protein enough for a 200lb man?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">For a 200lb man over 40, 100g per day falls just below the research-backed minimum of 1.2g/kg (109g). It's significantly better than average intake, but the per-meal distribution is the bigger problem: 100g spread across four meals averages only 25g per sitting — below the 30g threshold needed to trigger muscle protein synthesis after 40.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How much protein does a 200lb man need per day?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">A 200lb man (91kg) over 40 should target 109–145g of protein per day. The lower end (109g / 1.2g per kg) is the minimum for muscle preservation. The higher end (145g / 1.6g per kg) is appropriate for men who train regularly. If you're sedentary, 109g is your floor. If you're lifting, aim for 130–145g.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Why isn't 100g of protein enough to build muscle after 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Two compounding reasons. First, anabolic resistance — after 40, muscles respond less efficiently to protein, requiring higher daily totals to achieve the same muscle-preserving effect. Second, per-meal dosing: 100g divided across four meals is only 25g per sitting, below the 30g minimum threshold needed to trigger meaningful muscle protein synthesis in older adults.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What happens if a 200lb man only eats 100g of protein per day?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Nothing dramatic in the short term — that's the problem. Long-term, staying slightly below the protein floor contributes to gradual muscle loss (0.5–1% per year in your 40s, accelerating after 60), slower recovery, reduced strength, and a metabolism that responds less efficiently to training. The deficit is quiet but cumulative.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is 0.5g of protein per pound of bodyweight enough?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">For a 200lb man, 0.5g per pound equals exactly 100g — right below the 1.2g/kg minimum. It's far better than the RDA (which gives a 200lb man only 73g), but still short of the 0.7–0.8g per pound that research supports for active men over 40 focused on muscle preservation.</div>
